ific reasons to deny the reality of the self, but that we can lead healthier social and moral lives if we understand that we are selfless persons. The book describes why the Buddhist idea of no-self is so powerful and why it has immense practical benefits, helping us to abandon egoism, act more morally and ethically, be more spontaneous, perform more expertly, and navigate ordinary life more skillfully. Getting over the self-illusion also means escaping the isolation of self-identity and becoming a person who participates with others in the shared enterprise of life.The result is a transformative book about why we have nothing to lose—and everything to gain—by losing our selves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aBuddhismxDoctrines. 0aSelf (Philosophy). 7aPHILOSOPHY / Buddhist.2bisacsh  aAdult.  aAesthetics.  aAffection.  aAll things.  aAnalogy.  aArousal.  aArthur Schopenhauer.  aAttunement.  aAvicenna.  aAwareness.  aBanknote.  aCausality.  aChristian tradition.  aCogito ergo sum.  aComplication (medicine).  aConsciousness.  aContemporary philosophy.  aConvention (norm).  aCounterargument.  aDan Zahavi.  aDeed.  aDichotomy.  aDisposition.  aE pluribus unum.  aElaboration.  aEngineering.  aEtiquette.  aEtymology.  aExemption (church).  aExistence.  aExistential phenomenology.  aExplanation.  aFacial expression.  aFalsity.  aGalen Strawson.  aGeorge Berkeley.  aHatred.  aHigh Art.  aHomo sapiens.  aHypothesis.  aIdeology.  aIllusionism (philosophy).  aInfant.  aInference.  aInstitution.  aInteraction.  aInterdependence.  aIntuition.  aIslam.  aJingoism.  aLaurence Olivier.  aLiterature.  aLudwig Wittgenstein.  aMathematician.  aMaturity (psychological).  aMoral development.  aMotor control.  aNarrative.